  1. On the VPS: run WAHA bound to localhost only

  Don't expose port 3000 to the public internet — that's exactly how the account got banned in the GitHub issue we looked
  at earlier (open API → spam abuse → ban). Bind it to loopback only:

  docker run -d --name waha --restart always \
    -p 127.0.0.1:3000:3000 \
    -e WAHA_API_KEY=<your-key> \
    -e WHATSAPP_HOOK_URL=http://<ayt-sales-backend-host>:8080/api/webhooks/waha \
    -e WHATSAPP_HOOK_EVENTS=message \
    -e WAHA_DASHBOARD_USERNAME=admin \
    -e WAHA_DASHBOARD_PASSWORD=<pick-something> \
    devlikeapro/waha
  127.0.0.1:3000:3000 means WAHA is only reachable from the VPS itself — nothing external can hit it directly.

  If the ayt-sales backend runs on the same VPS: use --add-host=host.docker.internal:host-gateway in the docker run
  command (Linux needs this explicitly, unlike Docker Desktop on Mac) and point WHATSAPP_HOOK_URL at
  http://host.docker.internal:8080/.... If it's on a different server, use that server's real address over HTTPS.

  2. Reach WAHA securely via SSH tunnel (no public exposure needed)

  From your local machine:
  ssh -L 3000:localhost:3000 your-user@your-vps-ip
  Now http://localhost:3000 on your laptop transparently tunnels to the VPS's WAHA instance. Everything below — dashboard,
  QR, pairing code — works exactly like the local setup you already have, just through this tunnel.

  3. Create the session (same as before, plus the API key header)

  curl -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/sessions \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -H "X-Api-Key: <your-key>" \
    -d '{
      "name": "default",
      "config": {
        "webhooks": [{
          "url": "http://<ayt-sales-backend-host>:8080/api/webhooks/waha",
          "events": ["message"],
